                        <div class="player-info-bio">
                            <strong>Birthdate: </strong>4/23/1985 (32 y, 10 m, 15 d)<br /><strong>Contract:</strong> <a href="statss.aspx?playerid=4054&position=2B/OF#contract" >$1.2M / 1 Years (2016)</a>

                    <tr><td><hr class="player-page-info-sep"/><div class="player-page-rotowire"><strong><a href="http://www.rotowire.com/users/ad_jump.asp?id=688&playerid=9569">RotoWire News</a>:</strong> Bonifacio signed a minor-league deal with the Diamondbacks on Monday, Chris Cotillo of SB Nation reports. (7/31/2017)</div></td></tr>

                    <td>1/5/2015</td><td class="td-badge"><div class="fg badge">FG</div></td><td><a href="http://www.fangraphs.com/blogs/the-least-you-can-say-about-emilio-bonifacio/">The Least You Can Say About Emilio Bonifacio</a><span class="m_author"> by <a href="http://www.fangraphs.com/blogs/index.php?author=16">Carson Cistulli</a></span></td></tr><tr>

        <td style="width: 302px; height: 250px; vertical-align: top;">
            <div class="catchall300" style='width:300px; overflow:hidden;float:right;'><!-- RoS_300x250 --> <div id ='div-gpt-ad-1349421924281-13' style='width:300px; height:250px; overflow:hidden;'><script type='text/javascript'>if ($('#div-gpt-ad-1349421924281-13').is(':visible')) {googletag.cmd.push(function () { googletag.display('div-gpt-ad-1349421924281-13'); });}</script></div></div>

        </td>
    </tr>
    <tr>
        
        <tr id="so2" style="background-color: #FFF; display:none;"><td colspan="5" padding:3px; text-align:justify;"><div class="m_stories" style="font-size:10pt"><center><table><tr><td style="width:615px; padding-right:7px; text-align:justify;" valign="top"><b>Year in Review: </b>YEAR IN REVIEW: If you look up the definition of a replacement player in the sabermetric dictionary, you'll see a picture of Emilio Bonifacio. His .278 wOBA was the worst in the National League, and yet the Marlins kept trotting him out there, allowing him 509 plate appearances before the Nick Johnson trade moved Jorge Cantu over to third. So how did Bonifacio hold onto his job so long?  It’s hard to say, really. The Marlins organization could have called up Gaby Sanchez, who hit for a wRC+ of 126 in Triple-A. Perhaps Sanchez' lackluster spring training left a bad taste in his manager's mouth, but this case is exactly why you don't based your judgments of a player on a good or bad spring training. <br /><br /><b>The Year Ahead: </b>Bonifacio will be relegated to the bench in 2010, and you can't steal too many bases from the bench, which is one of Bonifacio's few good qualities. He should see some time all over the infield, where's he'll be the Marlins' designated Jack of All Trades, Master of None. If he does get playing time due to injuries of Hanley Ramirez, Dan Uggla or Cantu – and you really need some help in the speed department – Bonifacio could possibly surface as a short-term option.  (Erik Manning)</td></tr></table></center></div></td></tr>
        
        <tr id="so4" style="background-color: #FFF; display:none;"><td colspan="5" padding:3px; text-align:justify;"><div class="m_stories" style="font-size:10pt"><center><table><tr><td style="width:615px; padding-right:7px; text-align:justify;" valign="top"><b>Profile: </b>In 2011, Emilio Bonifacio had a career year. He posted a triple-slash line of .296/.360/.393 with 78 runs scored and 40 stolen bases. Those stolen bases were good for a tie for fourth in all of baseball, ahead of some premier speedsters. Bonifacio, 26, will also have great versatility headed into 2012 with eligibility at third base, second base, shortstop, and outfield. The big issue is that we've never seen this kind of production Bonifacio, and the concern that there will be a letdown in 2011 back towards his career norms. His batting average was buoyed by some good fortune with a .372 batting average on balls in play but with a 24% line drive rate and just a 23% fly ball rate, he earned almost all of it with an expected BABIP north of .360. It's probably optimistic to think he can repeat, but that doesn't mean Bonifacio doesn't still have a lot of value. He can be a great asset with his speed and his versatility would no doubt come in handy when injuries strike. (Michael Barr)<br /><br /><b>The Quick Opinion: </b>A carbon-copy repeat performance isn't likely for Bonifacio, but his plus speed and eligibility at shortstop, second base, third base and outfield make him a commodity worth owning.</td></tr></table></center></div></td></tr>
        <tr id="so5" style="background-color: #FFF; display:none;"><td colspan="5" padding:3px; text-align:justify;"><div class="m_stories" style="font-size:10pt"><center><table><tr><td style="width:615px; padding-right:7px; text-align:justify;" valign="top"><b>Profile: </b>After a breakout fantasy season in 2011, Bonifacio endured thumb and knee injuries last year that limited him to just 274 plate appearances. Already a strong contributor in stolen bases, he took that skill to a new level, swiping bases at a 91% success rate while on a pace for 66 steals over 600 plate appearances. His playing time in Toronto remains a bit murky, but at the very least, he'll fill in at second, third, and shortstop and in the outfield. His best opportunity may come at second base where he only has Maicer Izturis to fend off. Given his ability to play multiple positions and the potential to win semi-regular playing time at second, Bonifacio might well still garner over 400 at-bats this season. (<a target="blank" href="http://www.fangraphs.com/www.pallocale.com">Mike Podhorzer</a>)<br /><br /><b>The Quick Opinion: </b>After being traded to the Blue Jays, Bonifacio is likely to serve in a super-utility role, but could battle Maicer Izturis for the majority of second base at-bats. As usual, he'll be a strong source of speed and runs scored while on the field, but provide little else.</td></tr></table></center></div></td></tr>
        <tr id="so6" style="background-color: #FFF; display:none;"><td colspan="5" padding:3px; text-align:justify;"><div class="m_stories" style="font-size:10pt"><center><table><tr><td style="width:615px; padding-right:7px; text-align:justify;" valign="top"><b>Profile: </b>Bonifacio was a cheap source of speed for the last three seasons as he stole 98 bases in just 352 games. But he's going to have a difficult time getting to the plate enough to use his speed this year. The Royals signed Omar Infante to play second base which prompted the team to designate Bonifacio for assignment. It was possible that in addition to spelling Infante on occasion, Bonifacio could also spell Mike Moustakas at third from time to time. But the Royals also traded for Danny Valencia. Valencia, a right-handed hitter, has a career weighted offense that's 40% better than league average against lefties. He makes for a very good platoon partner with Mike Moustakas and even if third base doesn't end up being a straight platoon, Valencia is going to get the extra starts at the position. Prior to the Valencia trade, Steamer had Bonifacio projected for 277 plate appearances and 18 steals. But those numbers can't even really be his upside with Valencia in town, and there's no obvious starting role waiting for him elsewhere in the league. So it would seem that Bonifacio's days of limited fantasy relevance may be over. (<a href="https://twitter.com/TheRealTAL">Brett Talley</a>)<br /><br /><b>The Quick Opinion: </b>Bonifacio has been a cheap source of speed going on three years, but he's going to have a hard time getting to the plate enough to use his speed this year. There just won't be enough starts to go around in the Kansas City infield for Bonifacio to steal enough bags to be fantasy relevant, and it's unclear what other starting role could be found for him around the league.</td></tr></table></center></div></td></tr>
        <tr id="so7" style="background-color: #FFF; display:none;"><td colspan="5" padding:3px; text-align:justify;"><div class="m_stories" style="font-size:10pt"><center><table><tr><td style="width:615px; padding-right:7px; text-align:justify;" valign="top"><b>Profile: </b>Still the owner of a top 25 Speed Score, Bonifacio is projected by Steamer to steal 29 bases in the upcoming year. So he'll have value in many leagues, as flawed as he is. No power, no patience, no glove -- Bonifacio does not make for a great sleeper, even on a White Sox team without another veteran second baseman on the roster. With Carlos Sanchez and Micah Johnson in the fold, though, the south-siders have enough upside to look past Bonifacio at second. Considering the collapse possible in Conor Gillaspie's line, maybe he sneaks into more regular work at third. Most likely, the Good Face will back up second, third, and in the outfield. That would mean some value in deep batting average leagues as a plug-and-play steals source, but not much beyond.  (<a href="https://twitter.com/RotoBanter">Dan Schwartz</a>)<br /><br /><b>The Quick Opinion: </b>As a useful but flawed super utility man on a team with question marks at second and third, Bonifacio has a little bit of daylight left in his fantasy relevance. The team would probably rather the 30-year-old stays in the utility role, though, so don't overpay. </td></tr></table></center></div></td></tr>
        <tr id="so8" style="background-color: #FFF; display:none;"><td colspan="5" padding:3px; text-align:justify;"><div class="m_stories" style="font-size:10pt"><center><table><tr><td style="width:615px; padding-right:7px; text-align:justify;" valign="top"><b>Profile: </b>When Emilio Bonifacio signed with the White Sox last winter, it seemed that he would have an opportunity to make an impact as a versatile utility player with considerable speed (157 stolen bases in 662 games from 2009-14). The Dominican native did manage to play four different positions (and nine games at designated hitter) for Chicago, but his .167/.198/.192 batting line in 82 plate appearances was disappointing even by his light-hitting standards. Even more unsettling was his lack of speed production, as he swiped just one base and was caught four times. Bonifacio landed on the disabled list in late July and was released in August, and his minor league contract with the Cubs that month never led to a promotion. Bonifacio will turn 31 in April, and he now finds himself back on a rebuilding Braves team after signing with them in the offseason. He is expected to fill a utility role alongside Gordon Beckham as they back up players like Erick Aybar, Adonis Garcia, Hector Olivera, and Jace Peterson. With a lack of dependable playing time and no considerable power (career .337 slugging percentage) when he is in the lineup, Bonifacio will have a tough time stealing enough bases to make himself a useful option in most fantasy formats in '16. (Dylan Higgins)<br /><br /><b>The Quick Opinion: </b>Bonifacio certainly struggled last season, and his inability to even utilize his most valuable asset -- his speed -- is a serious cause for concern. The utility player finds himself in the right situation to bounce back, but he will need to do it with his bat as well as his legs if he is going to provide fantasy value again.</td></tr></table></center></div></td></tr>
        
    </tr>
</table>
